<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="428" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1544,2039]" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1617,1643]" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named after Cyrus II of 
<collectingCountry box="[800,868,1616,1642]" name="Iran" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">Persia</collectingCountry>
(c. 600–530 BC), commonly known as Cyrus the Great, the founder of the Achaemenid Empire, the first Persian empire; noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="428" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1544,2039]" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1688,1714]" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new species differs from its congeners in the region (i.e. 
<taxonomicName authority="Marusik, 2011" authorityName="Marusik" authorityYear="2011" box="[1008,1300,1688,1715]" class="Arachnida" family="Zodariidae" genus="Trygetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="428" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gromovi">
<emphasis box="[1008,1024,1689,1714]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">T</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1037,1129,1689,1714]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">gromovi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Marusik, Y. M." box="[1136,1300,1688,1715]" pageId="5" pageNumber="428" pagination="29 - 31" refId="ref6443" refString="Marusik, Y. M. (2011) A new Trygetus species from Central Asia (Araneae: Zodariidae). Turkish Journal of Zoology, 35, 29 - 31. https: // doi. org / 10.3906 / zoo- 0907 - 78" type="journal article" year="2011">Marusik, 2011</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2021" authorityName="Zamani &amp; Marusik" authorityYear="2021" class="Arachnida" family="Zodariidae" genus="Trygetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="428" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="susianus">
<emphasis box="[1311,1327,1689,1714]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">T</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1340,1436,1689,1714]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">susianus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Zamani, A. &amp; Marusik, Y. M." box="[151,440,1724,1751]" pageId="5" pageNumber="428" pagination="145 - 193" refId="ref6801" refString="Zamani, A. &amp; Marusik, Y. M. (2021) Revision of the spider family Zodariidae (Arachnida, Araneae) in Iran and Turkmenistan, with seventeen new species. ZooKeys, 1035, 145 - 193. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 1035.65767" type="journal article" year="2021">Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2021</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Marusik &amp; Guseinov, 2003" authorityName="Marusik &amp; Guseinov" authorityYear="2003" box="[497,940,1724,1751]" class="Arachnida" family="Zodariidae" genus="Trygetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="428" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jacksoni">
<emphasis box="[497,513,1725,1750]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">T</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[528,621,1724,1750]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">Jacksoni</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Marusik, Y. M. &amp; Guseinov, E." box="[629,940,1724,1751]" pageId="5" pageNumber="428" pagination="29 - 46" refId="ref6489" refString="Marusik, Y. M. &amp; Guseinov, E. (2003) Spiders (Arachnida: Aranei) of Azerbaijan. 1. New family and genus records. Arthropoda Selecta, 12, 29 - 46." type="journal article" year="2003">Marusik &amp; Guseinov, 2003</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
) by the lack of distinct epigynal fovea (
<emphasis box="[1396,1427,1725,1750]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">Fo</emphasis>
) (
<emphasis box="[161,191,1761,1786]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">vs.</emphasis>
present in other species), and by the parallel epigynal sclerotization (
<emphasis box="[988,1011,1761,1786]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">vs</emphasis>
. triangular or absent, cf. 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1220,1244]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1181]" captionTargetId="figure-17@7.[151,1436,181,1196]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. Epigynes of Trygetus nakhchivanicus sp. n. (A–C), T. gromovi Marusik, 2011 (D–F), T. susianus Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2021 (G–I) and T. Jacksoni Marusik &amp; Guseinov, 2003 (J). A, D, G vulva, dorsal; B, E, H, J intact epigyne, ventral; C, F macerated epigyne, ventral and antero-ventral; I right receptacle, dorsal. D–F after Marusik (2011), G–I after Zamani &amp; Marusik (2021) and J after Marusik &amp; Guseinov (2003). Scale bars: A–I = 0.2 mm (not provided for J). Abbreviations: Bu—bursa, Fo—fovea, Re—receptacle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683487" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683487/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">Fig. 6B and 6E, H, J</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="429" pageId="5" pageNumber="428" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1544,2039]" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1832,1858]" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">Description.</emphasis>
Female. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation box="[600,681,1832,1859]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1846,1870]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,348,1822]" captionTargetId="figure-87@6.[151,1436,345,1822]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 5. Habitus of Trygetus gromovi Marusik, 2011 (A–D), T. susianus Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2021 (E), T. cyrus sp. n. (F) and T. nakhchivanicus sp. n. (G, H). A, F female, dorsal; B same, lateral; C female’s abdomen and posterior part of cephalothorax, ventral; D female’s cephalothorax, anterior; E, H male, dorsal; G same, ventral. Scale bars = 0.2 mm, unless stated otherwise." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683485" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683485/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">
Fig. 
<specimenCount box="[651,681,1832,1859]" pageId="5" pageNumber="428" type="generic">5F</specimenCount>
</figureCitation>
. Total length 2.17. Carapace 0.92 long, 0.61 wide. Eye sizes: AME: 0.06, ALE: 0.05, PLE: 0.04. Carapace, sternum, labium, chelicerae and maxillae yellowish brown. Legs yellowish, without annulations. Abdomen dark grayish. Spinnerets pale, uniform in color. Measurements of legs: Fe I: 0.54, Fe II: 0.53, Pa II: 0.21, III: 1.62 (0.48, 0.22, 0.32, 0.32, 0.28), IV: 2.34 (0.63, 0.27, 0.52, 0.53, 0.39), unlisted segments missing.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1544,2039]" lastBlockId="6.[151,1436,151,321]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="429" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">
Epigyne as in 
<figureCitation box="[363,486,2012,2038]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1220,1244]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1181]" captionTargetId="figure-17@7.[151,1436,181,1196]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. Epigynes of Trygetus nakhchivanicus sp. n. (A–C), T. gromovi Marusik, 2011 (D–F), T. susianus Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2021 (G–I) and T. Jacksoni Marusik &amp; Guseinov, 2003 (J). A, D, G vulva, dorsal; B, E, H, J intact epigyne, ventral; C, F macerated epigyne, ventral and antero-ventral; I right receptacle, dorsal. D–F after Marusik (2011), G–I after Zamani &amp; Marusik (2021) and J after Marusik &amp; Guseinov (2003). Scale bars: A–I = 0.2 mm (not provided for J). Abbreviations: Bu—bursa, Fo—fovea, Re—receptacle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683487" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683487/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">Fig. 6A–C</figureCitation>
; plate broad, 2.5 times wider than long, fovea indistinct, hoods and pockets absent; median part with 2 parallel sclerotized structures; vulva consisted of membranous globular bursae (
<emphasis box="[1274,1305,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="429">Bu</emphasis>
) and round receptacles (
<emphasis box="[292,322,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="429">Re</emphasis>
), bursae separated by diameter of one receptacle, and receptacles separated almost by 3 diameters; copulatory ducts indistinct; fertilization ducts comma shaped.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,321]" box="[199,389,259,285]" pageId="6" pageNumber="429">Male. Unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1158,294,321]" pageId="6" pageNumber="429" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,321]" box="[199,1158,294,321]" pageId="6" pageNumber="429">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,294,320]" pageId="6" pageNumber="429">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[608,656,295,321]" pageId="6" pageNumber="429">type</typeStatus>
locality in 
<collectingRegion box="[783,941,295,321]" country="Iran" name="Fars" pageId="6" pageNumber="429">Fars Province</collectingRegion>
, south-central 
<collectingCountry box="[1105,1154,295,321]" name="Iran" pageId="6" pageNumber="429">Iran</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
